## Data visualization using Plotly Express -> Interactive graphs

# This treemap shows the population (represented by the size of the boxes) and the logarithmic GDP per capita (represented by the color) of various countries, grouped by region for the year 1990.
px.treemap(df1.query("year==1990"),color="log_GDPpc", values ="pop", path=("region","country"), hover_name="country", height=500)
In [14]:
px.choropleth(df1.query("year==1990"), locations="isocode", animation_frame="year", color="s", hover_name="country", projection="natural earth")
# This choropleth map shows a global visualization of the data, with countries colored based on the values of the their GDP for the year 1990.
In [16]:
px.line(df1, x="year", y="log_GDPpc", color="country", facet_col= "region")
# This line plot visualizes the logarithm of GDP per capita over time, with individual lines representing different countries and subplots (facets) grouping countries by region.
In [17]:
px.scatter(df1,
           animation_frame="year",
           x="s",
           y="log_lp",
           range_x= [0, 16],
           range_y= [7, 12.2],
           color="region",
           size="pop", size_max=60,
           hover_name="country",
           labels=dict(s="Years of Schooling",
                       log_lp="Labor productivity(in Logs)",
                       region="Continent",
                       pop= "Population")
           )
# This animated scatter plot visualizes the relationship between years of schooling and labor productivity (in logs) over time.
# Each point represents a country, with its size determined by the population and color representing the region/continent.
# The animation allows you to observe how this relationship evolves over the years, giving insights into the connection between education and productivity across different regions and populations.
